column1: i started collating information and resources for the women's net website at a time when i was feeling that women were being crushed and were losing our voice:
- gender pay gap reporting was unbelievably disheartening and shows we're still so far off equality in 2018
- trump's ""grab 'em by the x"" comment about how to treat women someone didn't dissuade a whole nation to vote him into power. the mind boggles
column2: and it boggles with disappointment and frustration behind it.

column1: - the #metoo movement crept out from the woodwork to show the far-reaching poison of men who've taken advantage of their 'power'
column2: and who thought they'd get away with it.

column1: i wanted to create a space to boost women up a few notches by making career advice and resources more accessible
column2: and really get into what we can do to achieve that lusted after sense of wellness and balance between work and our personal lives. if we can look after ourselves better
column3: we'll be in a much better position to take on worldwide equality.

column1: i was the teased kid. the abused kid. the odd ball. the artistic kid. the top athlete. i saw ghosts since i was little. the honors student. etc but i never felt like i ever fit in anywhere. i felt like an outcast. there was a hole. .

column1: 98257;instagram;2018-12-28 05:36:59;FALSE;"this was taken in tulum two weeks before i went to rehab. my face was such a mess ๐ฅ i had already made the decision to go to treatment.

i am a bit odd and went on a two week vacation to mexico for my birthday celebration and used it as my last drinking vacation. i was a highly functional alcoholic that never had any real consequences from my drinking so i took about a month to mentally prepare myself for treatment and have a last resort vacation with unlimited drinks.
however eventhough i had no legal issues or job losses and people told me i was ridiculous for getting help
column2: one of the guys that worked at the resort took me aside and told me he wished i could stop drinking because he was watching me and was worried about me.

column1: it was so sad because i had thought i was not drinking that much and surely no one could tell i had a drinking problem in mexico but he was sober and spotted me easily i imagine. i told him i was heading to treatment in a week and he was so happy for me.

the red spot in the middle of my eyes was from when i was drinking outside alone and dropped a glass of wine and it broke and i fell on it and the glass cut my face. i woke up covered in blood and thankful it didn't cut my eye. it took me six months to get help after that happened.  denial and fear held me back from admitting what was obviously a problem.

column1: i'm giving this letter to you now
column2: when you're eighteen years old and a line of separation has affected our relationship so much. and i know it's not your mistake.
you've lived confined to these four walls. i didn't  let you go to tuitions because while returning it's dark. i didn't let you study in a coed school
column3: because i feared the malicious intentions of guys which may robb me of my most precious stone during the late night school fair.

column1: i didn't give you your deserved freedom to feel your wings
column2: the winds and your abilities. till now
column3: you've lived on my terms. and this affected our bond. and now to you
column4: i'm just your strict father who robbed you of your life

column1: it was when you were one
column2: the little eight year old girl asifa
column3: became the victim of lost humanity in this world.

column1: i was really not that strong like asifa's father
column2: when i saw her smiling photograph i looked back to you. i feared that i may lose you one day.

column1: and i decided to do this.
when i saw tears in your eyes because of me
column2: i wished to melt down but then the unheard screams of pain of asifa used to hit my mind.

column1: when you came to me with a gleam of hope
column2: i wanted to behave like a fighter to make you one
column3: but the fear of losing you for it

column1: i'm sorry for not letting you out in the dark
column2: i'm sorry for making you dress according to my preferences
column3: i'm sorry for robbing your decision making abilities in your life
column4: but it was all for you!

column1: things were really bad that time
column4: the nation failed but all i knew that time was you
column5: your safety! you were the precious part of me
column6: and i wanted to keep it secured in my fraternal environment.

column1: i hope you understand and accept your father
column2: because he is not that bad atleast!
nunnu( this was what i used to call you)

column1: 98291;instagram;2018-12-28 04:20:32;FALSE;"never judge a book by it's cover. some people might seem fine on the outside
column2: but inside they could be struggling. i struggled these past few days with my mother's side of the family. i would like to share a story with you all. i was molested by my uncle when i was 13. i recently had the courage to tell my other family members about what happened and they do not believe me. i do not have proof
column3: but that does not mean that i do not have that memory that changed my life. i am a survivor. my family still invited my uncle to christmas and even had him lead the prayer
column4: which disgusted me to the very core. i want you all to know that you are not alone. there are people that will listen and care for you and they may not be blood. my best friends @princessfirefly and @spikeylovesyndrome helped me through my darkest times and showed me love that i never knew existed. they taught me that i have value and deserve love and respect. please do not think of ever harming yourself. suicide is not the answer. if you feel alone
column5: please call the suicide hotline or 911. they will listen and help.

column1: 98312;instagram;2018-12-28 04:47:52;FALSE;"an acronym occurred to me while i was pondering depression recently.  the shitty thing about depression is that it takes your alpha wave state captive and makes basic functions seem really foreign or strange. brains are funny things that are capable of amazing stuff and then forget to drink water.

it's winter and i know a lot of people struggle with cold and dark. i do- in high school i had to get a special lamp to simulate dawn so i could get out of bed every day. we are so intent on spreading cheer because we need to
column2: not just because we want to- i didn't get that until this year. dopamine deprivation is real.

i survived a really big jump off my ex boyfriend's balcony on the 4th floor. obvs it was a dark time... i was struggling regardless but then he essentially kidnapped me and violently tried to rape me. i don't share it a lot but it's not really that hard to tell i have been through shit by looking at me either. i had a lot of these elements going except i guess i stopped learning in my early 20s out of fatalism and heartbreak but if you play then learning becomes enjoyable.

column1: i'm feeling actually pretty good now despite being just out of the ""4th trimester"" and being at a parent's house and being in the suicide capital of the coast. this is my coping mechanism when i start to feel swallowed. it's simplified and excludes a lot of things one could use for levity but it works for me. . reaching out and saying something to someone even can help. get outside yourself

column1: 98344;instagram;2018-12-28 03:21:11;FALSE;"at the grocery store tonight i asked the clerk what his tattoo meant. it said ""f;ght""
column2: which to me could mean many things... he brought up a good point in his response. although mental health is being talked about more there is still a stigma attached to it. i realized how true this is because of my own life. i'm a survivor of many things and i'm also afraid to tell most people about them because of that stigma. however
column3: i've come to be extremely proud of myself. i still have sad days but i'm so proud of who i have become despite what life threw at me. .

column1: never give up fighting because time will pass and everything gets easier eventually. so hold on tight and keep fighting through the hard times.  life is about the choices you make and not just what happened to you. .

column2: i did self-harm when i was a teenager because i hurt so much
column3: that physically hurting myself stopped the mental pain for a short time. the thing to realize is that self-harm doesn't change or fix anything and it only temporarily distracts you. if you are going through a difficult time
column4: please know you aren't alone and there are people you can talk to. sometimes it helps just to talk out loud about things
column5: even to an animal. i've done it and i've also written letters that i've ripped up afterwards. i've even written similar posts to this before and deleted them... all this is to say
column6: keep fighting and working towards self love. never give up on yourself because you are worth more than you realize.โฅ๏ธ ๐ฆ .

column1: in a life filled with meaning and accomplishment
column2: michelle obama has emerged as one of the most iconic and compelling women of our era. as first lady of the united states of americaโthe first african-american to serve in that roleโshe helped create the most welcoming and inclusive white house in history
column3: while also establishing herself as a powerful advocate for women and girls in the u.s. and around the world
column4: dramatically changing the ways that families pursue healthier and more active lives
column5: and standing with her husband as he led america through some of its most harrowing moments. along the way
column6: she showed us a few dance moves
column8: and raised two down-to-earth daughters under an unforgiving media glare.

column2: a work of deep reflection and mesmerising storytelling
column3: michelle obama invites readers into her world
column4: chronicling the experiences that have shaped herโfrom her childhood on the south side of chicago to her years as an executive balancing the demands of motherhood and work
column5: to her time spent at the worldโs most famous address. with unerring honesty and lively wit
column6: she describes her triumphs and her disappointments
column8: telling her full story as she has lived itโin her own words and on her own terms.

column4: becoming is the deeply personal reckoning of a woman of soul and substance who has steadily defied expectationsโand whose story inspires us to do the same.

column1: 98560;instagram;2018-12-27 21:45:18;FALSE;"last night i dreamt of a saber-toothed tiger and then i was the protagonist of โwelcome to marwen.โ in dreams i was confronted by these bad guys and so i pulled a double barrel shotgun out of my handbag. they were scared of me...but my shotgun had this complex safety mechanism that made my weapon all but useless. โcome at meโ i said. this guyโs crazyโ they thought and proceeded to attack me. when i woke up i took it as a sign to go see this movie in the matinee showing

column1: dopo l'ultimo video di #kevinspacey credo sia arrivato il momento di parlare del mio problema con il #movimentometoo.

se sono d'accordissimo e felicissimo che qualcosa stia cambiando e della serie infinita di denunce che ci sono state e che hanno puntato il dito verso determinate persone e determinati comportamenti io credo che ci sia un problema generale con l'#after denuncia.

se infatti non ho problemi con una donna o un uomo che denuncia un abuso non sono minimamente d'accordo con la messa al bando istantanea della persona denunciata senza che vengano prima fatte delle opportune indagini.

allo stesso tempo se la persona in questione non viene condannata in nessun modo si deve trovare un modo per riportarlo sullo schermo o sul palcoscenico mettendo fine al suo calvario perchรจ magari non ha fatto nulla e si รจ sempre innocenti sino a prova contraria.
capisco tutto ma non posso credere per partito preso ad una denuncia perchรจ non รจ giusto.
si deve trovare un modo per rimettere al loro posto chi ne รจ uscito indenne.

this pic was clicked at komic - a village near kaza claimed to be the highest village in the world with a motorable road and the site of the world's highest homestay. i still remember stopping my bike every 5-7 minutes while approaching this village to rub my palms and make sure that my hands don't fall numb in the cold. but like the wise men say - harder the effort
